Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-13_task-things_run-6_desc-sdc_part-mag_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-13_task-things_run-6_desc-bbregister_part-mag_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-13_task-things_run-6_desc-rois_part-mag_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-13_task-things_run-6_desc-compcorvar_part-mag_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-13_task-things_run-6_desc-carpetplot_part-mag_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-13_task-things_run-6_desc-confoundcorr_part-mag_bold.svg

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-14_task-things_run-3_desc-sdc_part-mag_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-14_task-things_run-3_desc-bbregister_part-mag_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-14_task-things_run-3_desc-rois_part-mag_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-14_task-things_run-3_desc-compcorvar_part-mag_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-14_task-things_run-3_desc-carpetplot_part-mag_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-14_task-things_run-3_desc-confoundcorr_part-mag_bold.svg

Reports for: session 14, task things, run 4.

Summary
  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s
  • Phase-encoding (PE) direction: Anterior-Posterior
  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-14_task-things_run-6_desc-sdc_part-mag_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-14_task-things_run-6_desc-bbregister_part-mag_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-14_task-things_run-6_desc-rois_part-mag_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-14_task-things_run-6_desc-compcorvar_part-mag_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-14_task-things_run-6_desc-carpetplot_part-mag_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-14_task-things_run-6_desc-confoundcorr_part-mag_bold.svg

Reports for: session 15, task things, run 1.

Summary
  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s
  • Phase-encoding (PE) direction: Anterior-Posterior
  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-15_task-things_run-2_desc-carpetplot_part-mag_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-15_task-things_run-2_desc-confoundcorr_part-mag_bold.svg

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-15_task-things_run-3_desc-sdc_part-mag_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-15_task-things_run-3_desc-bbregister_part-mag_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-15_task-things_run-3_desc-rois_part-mag_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-15_task-things_run-3_desc-compcorvar_part-mag_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-15_task-things_run-5_desc-bbregister_part-mag_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-15_task-things_run-5_desc-rois_part-mag_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-15_task-things_run-5_desc-compcorvar_part-mag_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-15_task-things_run-5_desc-carpetplot_part-mag_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-15_task-things_run-5_desc-confoundcorr_part-mag_bold.svg

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-16_task-things_run-2_desc-sdc_part-mag_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-16_task-things_run-2_desc-bbregister_part-mag_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-16_task-things_run-2_desc-rois_part-mag_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-16_task-things_run-2_desc-compcorvar_part-mag_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-16_task-things_run-2_desc-carpetplot_part-mag_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-16_task-things_run-2_desc-confoundcorr_part-mag_bold.svg

Reports for: session 16, task things, run 3.

Summary
  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s
  • Phase-encoding (PE) direction: Anterior-Posterior
  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-16_task-things_run-5_desc-sdc_part-mag_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-16_task-things_run-5_desc-bbregister_part-mag_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-16_task-things_run-5_desc-rois_part-mag_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-16_task-things_run-5_desc-compcorvar_part-mag_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-16_task-things_run-5_desc-carpetplot_part-mag_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-16_task-things_run-5_desc-confoundcorr_part-mag_bold.svg

Reports for: session 16, task things, run 6.

Summary
  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s

  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-17_task-things_run-2_desc-sdc_part-mag_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-17_task-things_run-2_desc-bbregister_part-mag_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-17_task-things_run-2_desc-rois_part-mag_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-17_task-things_run-2_desc-compcorvar_part-mag_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-17_task-things_run-2_desc-carpetplot_part-mag_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-17_task-things_run-2_desc-confoundcorr_part-mag_bold.svg

Reports for: session 17, task things, run 3.

Summary
  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s
  • Phase-encoding (PE) direction: Anterior-Posterior
  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-17_task-things_run-4_desc-carpetplot_part-mag_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-17_task-things_run-5_desc-bbregister_part-mag_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-17_task-things_run-5_desc-rois_part-mag_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-18_task-things_run-1_desc-sdc_part-mag_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-18_task-things_run-1_desc-bbregister_part-mag_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-18_task-things_run-1_desc-rois_part-mag_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-18_task-things_run-1_desc-compcorvar_part-mag_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-18_task-things_run-1_desc-carpetplot_part-mag_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-18_task-things_run-1_desc-confoundcorr_part-mag_bold.svg

Reports for: session 18, task things, run 2.

Summary
  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s
  • Phase-encoding (PE) direction: Anterior-Posterior
  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-18_task-things_run-4_desc-sdc_part-mag_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-18_task-things_run-4_desc-bbregister_part-mag_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-18_task-things_run-4_desc-rois_part-mag_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-18_task-things_run-4_desc-compcorvar_part-mag_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-18_task-things_run-4_desc-carpetplot_part-mag_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-18_task-things_run-4_desc-confoundcorr_part-mag_bold.svg

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-19_task-things_run-1_desc-sdc_part-mag_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-19_task-things_run-1_desc-bbregister_part-mag_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-19_task-things_run-1_desc-rois_part-mag_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-19_task-things_run-1_desc-compcorvar_part-mag_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-19_task-things_run-1_desc-carpetplot_part-mag_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-19_task-things_run-1_desc-confoundcorr_part-mag_bold.svg

Reports for: session 19, task things, run 2.

Summary
  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s

  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-19_task-things_run-4_desc-sdc_part-mag_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-19_task-things_run-4_desc-bbregister_part-mag_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-19_task-things_run-4_desc-rois_part-mag_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-19_task-things_run-4_desc-compcorvar_part-mag_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-19_task-things_run-4_desc-carpetplot_part-mag_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-19_task-things_run-4_desc-confoundcorr_part-mag_bold.svg

Reports for: session 20, task things, run 1.

Summary
  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s
  • Phase-encoding (PE) direction: Anterior-Posterior
  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-20_task-things_run-2_desc-carpetplot_part-mag_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-20_task-things_run-3_desc-bbregister_part-mag_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-20_task-things_run-3_desc-rois_part-mag_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-20_task-things_run-5_desc-rois_part-mag_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-20_task-things_run-5_desc-compcorvar_part-mag_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-20_task-things_run-5_desc-carpetplot_part-mag_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-20_task-things_run-5_desc-confoundcorr_part-mag_bold.svg

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-21_task-things_run-2_desc-sdc_part-mag_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-21_task-things_run-2_desc-bbregister_part-mag_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-21_task-things_run-2_desc-rois_part-mag_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-21_task-things_run-2_desc-compcorvar_part-mag_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-21_task-things_run-2_desc-carpetplot_part-mag_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-21_task-things_run-2_desc-confoundcorr_part-mag_bold.svg

Reports for: session 21, task things, run 3.

Summary
  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s
  • Phase-encoding (PE) direction: Anterior-Posterior
  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-21_task-things_run-5_desc-sdc_part-mag_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-21_task-things_run-5_desc-bbregister_part-mag_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-21_task-things_run-5_desc-rois_part-mag_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-21_task-things_run-5_desc-compcorvar_part-mag_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-21_task-things_run-5_desc-carpetplot_part-mag_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-21_task-things_run-5_desc-confoundcorr_part-mag_bold.svg

Reports for: session 21, task things, run 6.

Summary
  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s

  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-22_task-things_run-2_desc-sdc_part-mag_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-22_task-things_run-2_desc-bbregister_part-mag_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-22_task-things_run-2_desc-rois_part-mag_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-22_task-things_run-2_desc-compcorvar_part-mag_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-22_task-things_run-2_desc-carpetplot_part-mag_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-22_task-things_run-2_desc-confoundcorr_part-mag_bold.svg

Reports for: session 22, task things, run 3.

Summary
  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s

  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-22_task-things_run-5_desc-sdc_part-mag_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-22_task-things_run-5_desc-bbregister_part-mag_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-22_task-things_run-5_desc-rois_part-mag_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-22_task-things_run-5_desc-compcorvar_part-mag_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-22_task-things_run-5_desc-carpetplot_part-mag_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-22_task-things_run-5_desc-confoundcorr_part-mag_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-23_task-things_run-1_desc-carpetplot_part-mag_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-23_task-things_run-4_desc-bbregister_part-mag_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-23_task-things_run-4_desc-rois_part-mag_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-23_task-things_run-4_desc-compcorvar_part-mag_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-23_task-things_run-4_desc-carpetplot_part-mag_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-23_task-things_run-4_desc-confoundcorr_part-mag_bold.svg

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-24_task-things_run-1_desc-sdc_part-mag_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-24_task-things_run-1_desc-bbregister_part-mag_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-24_task-things_run-1_desc-rois_part-mag_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-24_task-things_run-1_desc-compcorvar_part-mag_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-24_task-things_run-1_desc-carpetplot_part-mag_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-24_task-things_run-1_desc-confoundcorr_part-mag_bold.svg

Reports for: session 24, task things, run 2.

  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-24_task-things_run-4_desc-sdc_part-mag_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-24_task-things_run-4_desc-bbregister_part-mag_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-24_task-things_run-4_desc-rois_part-mag_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-24_task-things_run-4_desc-compcorvar_part-mag_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-24_task-things_run-4_desc-carpetplot_part-mag_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-24_task-things_run-4_desc-confoundcorr_part-mag_bold.svg

  • Date preprocessed: 2022-04-11 22:56:04 +0000

Methods

We kindly ask to report results preprocessed with this tool using the following boilerplate.

  • HTML
  • Markdown
  • LaTeX

Results included in this manuscript come from preprocessing performed using fMRIPrep 20.2.5 (Esteban, Markiewicz, et al. (2018); Esteban, Blair, et al. (2018); RRID:SCR_016216), which is based on Nipype 1.6.1 (Gorgolewski et al. (2011); Gorgolewski et al. (2018); RRID:SCR_002502).

Anatomical data preprocessing

A total of 0 T1-weighted (T1w) images were found within the input BIDS dataset. Anatomical preprocessing was reused from previously existing derivative objects.

Functional data preprocessing

For each of the 6 BOLD runs found per subject (across all tasks and sessions), the following preprocessing was performed. First, a reference volume and its skull-stripped version were generated by aligning and averaging 1 single-band references (SBRefs). A B0-nonuniformity map (or fieldmap) was estimated based on two (or more) echo-planar imaging (EPI) references with opposing phase-encoding directions, with 3dQwarp Cox and Hyde (1997) (AFNI 20160207). Based on the estimated susceptibility distortion, a corrected EPI (echo-planar imaging) reference was calculated for a more accurate co-registration with the anatomical reference. The BOLD reference was then co-registered to the T1w reference using bbregister (FreeSurfer) which implements boundary-based registration (Greve and Fischl 2009). Co-registration was configured with six degrees of freedom. Head-motion parameters with respect to the BOLD reference (transformation matrices, and six corresponding rotation and translation parameters) are estimated before any spatiotemporal filtering using mcflirt (FSL 5.0.9, Jenkinson et al. 2002). BOLD runs were slice-time corrected to 0.686s (0.5 of slice acquisition range 0s-1.37s) using 3dTshift from AFNI 20160207 (Cox and Hyde 1997, RRID:SCR_005927). First, a reference volume and its skull-stripped version were generated using a custom methodology of fMRIPrep. The BOLD time-series were resampled onto the following surfaces (FreeSurfer reconstruction nomenclature): fsaverage. The BOLD time-series (including slice-timing correction when applied) were resampled onto their original, native space by applying a single, composite transform to correct for head-motion and susceptibility distortions. These resampled BOLD time-series will be referred to as preprocessed BOLD in original space, or just preprocessed BOLD. The BOLD time-series were resampled into standard space, generating a preprocessed BOLD run in MNI152NLin2009cAsym space. First, a reference volume and its skull-stripped version were generated using a custom methodology of fMRIPrep. Grayordinates files (Glasser et al. 2013) containing 91k samples were also generated using the highest-resolution fsaverage as intermediate standardized surface space. Several confounding time-series were calculated based on the preprocessed BOLD: framewise displacement (FD), DVARS and three region-wise global signals. FD was computed using two formulations following Power (absolute sum of relative motions, Power et al. (2014)) and Jenkinson (relative root mean square displacement between affines, Jenkinson et al. (2002)). FD and DVARS are calculated for each functional run, both using their implementations in Nipype (following the definitions by Power et al. 2014). The three global signals are extracted within the CSF, the WM, and the whole-brain masks. Additionally, a set of physiological regressors were extracted to allow for component-based noise correction (CompCor, Behzadi et al. 2007). Principal components are estimated after high-pass filtering the preprocessed BOLD time-series (using a discrete cosine filter with 128s cut-off) for the two CompCor variants: temporal (tCompCor) and anatomical (aCompCor). tCompCor components are then calculated from the top 2% variable voxels within the brain mask. For aCompCor, three probabilistic masks (CSF, WM and combined CSF+WM) are generated in anatomical space. The implementation differs from that of Behzadi et al. in that instead of eroding the masks by 2 pixels on BOLD space, the aCompCor masks are subtracted a mask of pixels that likely contain a volume fraction of GM. This mask is obtained by dilating a GM mask extracted from the FreeSurfer’s aseg segmentation, and it ensures components are not extracted from voxels containing a minimal fraction of GM. Finally, these masks are resampled into BOLD space and binarized by thresholding at 0.99 (as in the original implementation). Components are also calculated separately within the WM and CSF masks. For each CompCor decomposition, the k components with the largest singular values are retained, such that the retained components’ time series are sufficient to explain 50 percent of variance across the nuisance mask (CSF, WM, combined, or temporal). The remaining components are dropped from consideration. The head-motion estimates calculated in the correction step were also placed within the corresponding confounds file. The confound time series derived from head motion estimates and global signals were expanded with the inclusion of temporal derivatives and quadratic terms for each (Satterthwaite et al. 2013). Frames that exceeded a threshold of 0.5 mm FD or 1.5 standardised DVARS were annotated as motion outliers. All resamplings can be performed with a single interpolation step by composing all the pertinent transformations (i.e. head-motion transform matrices, susceptibility distortion correction when available, and co-registrations to anatomical and output spaces). Gridded (volumetric) resamplings were performed using antsApplyTransforms (ANTs), configured with Lanczos interpolation to minimize the smoothing effects of other kernels (Lanczos 1964). Non-gridded (surface) resamplings were performed using mri_vol2surf (FreeSurfer). thresholding at 0.99 (as in the original implementation).

values are retained, such that the retained components' time series are
sufficient to explain 50 percent of variance across the nuisance mask (CSF,
WM, combined, or temporal). The remaining components are dropped from
consideration.
